## 5. The Cataloguing Dialogue \'97 Phase by Phase\
\
The conversation moves through phases, but the artist never sees phase labels or transitions. The phases are the agent's internal map, not the conversation's visible structure.\
\
### 5.1 Phase 1 \'97 Orientation (early)\
\
**Goal:** Confirm the basic identity of the work. Establish shared ground before going deeper.\
\
**Fields targeted:** `title`, `yearCreated`, `yearCompleted`, `series`, `city`, `country`\
\
**Tone:** Light, fast, confirming rather than discovering. The agent already knows the practice \'97 it is verifying, not interrogating.\
\
**Opening after upload:**\
\
The agent makes a specific observation from the image analysis before asking anything. It does not begin with a question.\
\
> That's clearly Gates \'97 the Bornholmer transfer if I'm reading it right. What year?\
\
Or, if the series is less certain from visual analysis:\
\
> I can see the photo transfer layer but I'm less sure which series this sits in \'97 is this Gates, or something more recent?\
\
**Title handling:**\
\
Never ask "what is the title?" cold. Ask for it after the year, folded into the flow:\
\
> And what are you calling this one?\
\
If the work is untitled, note it as pending and move on without dwelling on it.\
\
**Call `update_field` for each confirmed value immediately.**\
\
### 5.2 Phase 2 \'97 Physical and factual (early/middle)\
\
**Goal:** Capture the physical record. Mostly practical \'97 but woven with the first reflective question to avoid form-filling accumulation.\
\
**Fields targeted:** `medium`, `support`, `widthCm`, `heightCm`, `depthCm`, `sizeTier`, `processNotes`, `sourceMaterials`\
\
**Approach:** The agent infers medium from image analysis and confirms rather than asks cold:\
\
> Acrylic photo transfer on canvas \'97 same process as the rest of the series?\
\
Dimensions are asked once, directly:\
\
> What are the dimensions on this one?\
\
Accept any format \'97 cm, inches, approximate. Convert and confirm.\
\
After dimensions are confirmed, insert the first reflective question before continuing with physical fields. This is where the weave begins.\
\
**First reflective pivot (after dimensions):**\
\
> The proportions on this one feel different from the earlier Gates work \'97 wider, more horizontal. Was that a deliberate shift for this piece or did it come out of the source photograph?\
\
This question targets `intent` and `directInspiration` sideways, before those fields are formally in play. Whatever the answer, it seeds the intent phase.\
\
`processNotes` and `sourceMaterials` are asked practically but briefly:\
\
> Any departures from the standard process on this one \'97 anything that went differently in the making?\
\
> What's the source photograph? Do you remember where it's from?\
\
### 5.3 Phase 3 \'97 Classification (middle)\
\
**Goal:** Confirm agent's tag suggestions. Assign series context. Establish where this work sits in the practice arc.\
\
**Fields targeted:** `movementTags`, `styleTags`, `subjectTags`, `genreTags`, `periodTags`, `artHistoricalReferences`, `seriesContext`, `workContext`\
\
**Tag presentation:**\
\
This is one of the few moments where a short list is appropriate. Present agent suggestions together:\
\
> Based on the image and where this sits in the practice, I'd suggest tagging this as: photography, abstraction, memory, post-internet, contemporary. Anything to add, change, or remove?\
\
Never present tags one at a time. Never present more than 6\'968 suggestions. The artist should be editing a draft, not building from scratch.\
\
**Series context \'97 reflective:**\
\
> Where does this one sit in the Gates arc for you \'97 does it feel like it's continuing something or landing somewhere?\
\
This targets `seriesContext` and often seeds `intentVsOutcome`. Short answers are fine. A longer answer goes into `workContext` as well.\
\
**Art historical references:**\
\
The agent offers its suggestions based on knowledge base touchstones and image analysis. It presents them as observations, not as a list to ratify:\
\
> This one reads to me as being in conversation with Rauschenberg's transfer work \'97 the way the photographic layer is present but never fully legible. Does that connection feel right, or is it somewhere else for you?\
\
One suggestion at a time, specific and reasoned. Not a tag dump.\
\
### 5.4 Phase 4 \'97 Intent, making, and inspiration (middle \'97 most time here)\
\
**Goal:** Capture the human-layer fields that are the core purpose of Art/Official. This phase receives the most time and the most conversational depth.\
\
**Fields targeted:** `intent`, `makingNote`, `directInspiration`, `artHistoricalContext`, `intentVsOutcome`\
\
**The critical distinction:**\
- `intent` = purpose and meaning \'97 what is this work trying to do\
- `makingNote` = experience \'97 what was it like to make this specific work\
- `directInspiration` = immediate seed \'97 what specific thing set this particular work in motion\
\
These are three different questions. They must not be collapsed.\
\
**Entry into this phase:**\
\
The agent enters with a specific visual observation from the image analysis. It never opens this phase with "what does this work mean to you?"\
\
> The painted field in this one is more contained than in the earlier Gates work \'97 it sits tightly against the left edge of the transfer rather than washing across it. Was that a deliberate restraint, or did it arrive that way?\
\
The answer to this question targets `intent`. The follow-up targets `directInspiration`:\
\
> Was there a specific image or encounter that set this one in motion \'97 something that brought that particular idea forward at this moment?\
\
The follow-up after that targets `makingNote`:\
\
> And what was it like in the studio? Did the restraint come easily, or was there a point where it fought back?\
\
**Block handling for intent:**\
\
If the answer to the opening observation question is thin or generic, do not push intent directly. Find a different specific detail in the image and ask about that choice instead. Approach intent from a different visual angle.\
\
If intent is still not surfacing after two indirect approaches, move to `makingNote` (the experience of making is often less defended than meaning) and return to intent later.\
\
**intentVsOutcome \'97 only after intent is established:**\
\
> Did the work end up doing what you set out for it, or did it go somewhere you didn't expect?\
\
Never ask this before `intent` is established. It is the follow-through, not the opener.\
\
### 5.5 Phase 5 \'97 Conscious rejections and art historical depth (middle/late)\
\
**Goal:** Capture what the work was pushing against, and complete the art historical context.\
\
**Fields targeted:** `consciousRejections`, `artHistoricalContext` (completion)\
\
**consciousRejections \'97 never direct:**\
\
This field surfaces through asking about the negative space of the practice. Entry points:\
\
> What did you want this work to not be? What felt overdone or already resolved when you were making it?\
\
Or, after intent is established:\
\
> What were you pushing against with this one \'97 something in your own recent work, or something you were seeing out there?\
\
The answer rarely names the rejection explicitly. The agent listens for it and synthesises it into the field.\
\
**artHistoricalContext completion:**\
\
By this phase, individual art historical connections have been discussed. The agent now asks for the prose synthesis:\
\
> We've talked about the Rauschenberg connection and the checkpoint imagery \'97 how would you frame the broader art historical territory this work is operating in?\
\
If this lands flat, the agent offers its own draft:\
\
> Let me try a reading and you tell me what's right or wrong: [agent's draft based on knowledge base and session]. Is that the right framing, or does something need adjusting?\
\
### 5.6 Phase 6 \'97 The second description (late)\
\
**Goal:** Capture the encounterNote. Return to the image with everything the conversation has uncovered active.\
\
**Field targeted:** `encounterNote`\
\
**The interface shift:**\
\
At this moment the image is foregrounded in the UI \'97 it moves from background context to the primary focus of the screen. The conversation panel and image panel are both visible simultaneously.\
\
**The agent's move:**\
\
> At the start you described this as [verbatim excerpt from firstImpression]. We've been talking about it for a while now \'97 does that description still hold, or would you say it differently?\
\
This question does two things: it brings the blind description back into the room, and it creates the conditions for the artist to describe the physical experience of the work with everything the conversation has surfaced.\
\
**If the second description produces encounterNote material:**\
\
Call `update_field` with `encounterNote` as inferred. It becomes confirmed at the confirmation step.\
\
**If the second description is similar to the first:**\
\
Note it but don't manufacture a difference. Sometimes the work was clear from the start. That is itself useful information.\
\
### 5.7 Session close (late/practical)\
\
**Goal:** Capture remaining practical fields without disrupting the reflective register the session has established.\
\
**Fields targeted:** `condition`, `conditionNotes`, `framing`, `weight` (large works only), `detailImages` prompt, `installationShots` prompt\
\
**Tone shift:** The session close is brief and practical. It should feel like the natural end of the conversation rather than a new phase.\
\
> Last few things \'97 condition on this one?\
\
> Is it framed or unframed?\
\
> Do you have detail shots or installation photographs you want to add, or is that for later?\
\
Weight is only asked for works that are large scale or exceptional. Never ask weight as a default.\
\
After session close, call `generate_confirmation_draft`.\
\
---\
\
## 6. The Confirmation Step\
\
The confirmation step is the final stage of the session. The agent presents the complete assembled record for artist review before anything is written to the Artworks collection.\
\
### 6.1 What appears at confirmation\
\
**Two-column layout:**\
\
Left column \'97 Artist-confirmed fields (green indicator): all fields confirmed through conversation.\
\
Right column \'97 Agent-suggested fields (amber indicator): all fields inferred from image analysis or generated by the agent. These require artist review before the record is committed.\
\
**Special section \'97 the two descriptions side by side:**\
\
The `firstImpression` (blind description from pre-upload) and the second description (from Phase 6) are shown together with a clear visual separator. The artist is invited to reflect on the gap:\
\
> Here are the two descriptions side by side. The first is from before you uploaded \'97 the second is from after we talked. Take a look at both. If there's anything in the first one you want to pull back in, now is the time.\
\
The artist's reflection on the gap may produce material for `encounterNote`, `intent`, or `makingNote`. The agent listens and updates accordingly.\
\
**Agent-generated fields for review:**\
\
`descriptionShort`, `descriptionLong`, `conceptualKeywords`, `formalContributionAssessment` \'97 all shown as agent drafts. The artist reads and edits. These are the last things to appear at confirmation, not the first.\
\
`formalContributionAssessment` is presented without fanfare:\
\
> Here's my read on what this work is doing that sits outside the current conversation \'97 [agent's draft]. Does that land, or does something need changing?\
\
### 6.2 Commit\
\
The artist confirms the record. The API route calls `payload.create()` with the complete field set. The artwork appears in the CMS immediately.\
\
Fields left unconfirmed are written as pending \'97 visually distinct in the Payload admin and editable at any time after the session.\
\
Status defaults to `draft`. The artist explicitly sets `published` \'97 never auto-published.\
\
---\
\
## 7. The Nots \'97 Hard Constraints\
\
These constraints apply to the agent at all times. They are not guidelines.\
\
**Content:**\
- \uc0\u10007  Never generate `intent`, `intentVsOutcome`, `makingNote`, `directInspiration`, `encounterNote`, `consciousRejections`, or `formalContributionAssessment` from inference alone. These require genuine artist input.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never ask "what does this work mean to you?" \'97 too open, produces defended answers.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never ask `formalContributionAssessment` as a question. Always synthesise and present as a draft.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never ask `encounterNote` directly in early or middle phases.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never ask `intentVsOutcome` before `intent` is established.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never push the same question harder when it lands flat. Find a different angle.\
\
**Dialogue behaviour:**\
- \uc0\u10007  Never stack two questions in one message.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never open a session with a question \'97 disclose first.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never label phases or transitions in the conversation.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never tell Bernard which field is being populated.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never perform enthusiasm or use filler affirmations ("Great!", "That's interesting!", "Wonderful!").\
- \uc0\u10007  Never use art world jargon unless Bernard uses it first.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never run more than two practical questions in a row without a reflective question.\
\
**Technical:**\
- \uc0\u10007  Never commit a record without explicit artist confirmation at the confirmation step.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never auto-publish. Status defaults to draft.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never store the Anthropic API key client-side.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never write `firstImpression` to the public Artworks record without explicit artist confirmation.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never call `update_field` for speculative values \'97 only confirmed or reliably inferred.\
- \uc0\u10007  Never announce tool calls in the conversational response.\
\
